Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout for the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have continued to balloon as house prices have fallen.
Now that the government is completely liable for Fannies and Freddies debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for all that is not covered by the insufficient financial means of their creditors.
Why such a rescue action in the most overtly capitalist country in the world?
Do not the venerable principles of capitalism include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that now innocent taxpayers have to bear the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Mostly unclear is whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector, and therefore the global economy, to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being equipped with an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a US government rescue operation could undermine confidence in government securities – and because they are linked to these – also in other financial titles.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values over the past few years, which introduces questions of trust, but also fairness into the equation.
Similar housing sector highs in many other countries are also coming to an end at present, and they may be facing the same torments – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem are not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose between 2005 and 2007 by a factor of 5 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose between 2003 and 2007 by a factor of 5 in real terms and has lost a third of its value since then.
Similar highs and crashes of the stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they continued, the preceding boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a decline in trust could seize the world economy and push it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help is lacking.
The people's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described altitude flights and crashes have caused a great redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or on the housing market cut in either good or bad timing.
The people will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and which implicit promises they derived from them.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
The policy can only react generally and not treat all cases individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times was spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments sold too expensively into their markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere seduced people into believing that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been plenty of "cheap talk" – general advice under reserve –, most of the losers in this game are not scratching at the bread bowl.
However, we cannot conclude from this without concern that one should leave all their losses unrestricted.
The nagging problem is one of "Faith and Loyalty".
Peoples' economies only flourish when "Faith and Loyalty" reign.
The current situation, in which speculative highs have driven the global economy – and now, after their collapse, drive it into a recession –, suggests that people who have been promoting certain investments, have done so in bad faith and against loyalty.
Take the investors who issued Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out in case of emergency, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The government's top officials never issued any warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of transforming capitalism and its power into discovering economies.
However, capitalism is dependent on good faith.
A perceived unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people will lose their trust in the companies and therefore be less willing to provide them with their precious capital and labor.
Is a result like this morally preferable to a bailout?
